\begin_layout Enumerate

\emph on
Credits: 5p.

\emph default
 Derive the predictive distribution of a new observation 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n+1}$
\end_inset

 from the same model as in 3(a).
 An expression is enough, you don't need to recognize the distributional
 family.

\series bold
\color blue
 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Solution
\series default
\color inherit
: The predictive distribution of a new observation 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n+1}$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
p(x_{n+1}\vert x_{1},...,x_{n}) & =\int p(x_{n+1}\vert\theta)p(\theta\vert x_{1},...,x_{n})d\theta\\
 & =\int\left(\begin{array}{c}
m\\
x_{n+\text{1}}
\end{array}\right)\theta^{x_{n+1}}(1-\theta)^{m-x_{n+1}}\\
 & \times\frac{1}{B(\alpha+\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i},\beta+nm-\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i})}\theta^{\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}+\alpha-1}(\text{1-\theta})^{nm-\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}+\beta-1}d\theta\\
 & \propto\left(\begin{array}{c}
m\\
x_{n+\text{1}}
\end{array}\right)\int\theta^{x_{n+1}+\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}+\alpha-1}(1-\theta)^{nm-\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}+m-x_{n+1}+\beta-1}d\theta\\
 & =\left(\begin{array}{c}
m\\
x_{n+\text{1}}
\end{array}\right)B(x_{n+1}+\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}+\alpha,nm+m-\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}-x_{n+1}+\beta)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This distribution can be further simplified, but this is enough for full
 credit.
